Not only will he be without a couple key weapons (WR Antonio Callaway, RB Jordan Scarlett), he's facing a notoriously well-coached, aggressive Don Brown defense that forced a higher percentage of plays for zero or negative yards than anyone in the FBS last season.

I don't have anything to say about it. ... I'll probably pace around a little bit, stress out and hopefully somebody will be in there to calm me down. I'm not going to get my energy up to high until I'm about to go in because I don't want to waste it."

          Carson Wise is taking over placekicking duties for NC State this year, but Kyle Bambard still has a role as the team's kickoff specialist. Bambard endured death threats and nasty taunts after missing a kick against Clemson that would have won the game. Yet he never considered quitting the team, telling coach Dave Doeren, "Coach, I love NC State. You gave me this opportunity. I love these kids, these teammates. I'm going to do everything I can to get better. Whatever my role is, I'll accept it." Doeren said that attitude showed Bambard's strength and resilience. "All of us that know what he went through, to see how he's handled it is very impressive," Doeren said.
